Step 1 - Familiarize yourself with the data and the assignment

Save this file as a new Quarto Markdown document and name it something that includes your last name in the filename. Save it into the same folder as this file. Create a new R Studio Project based on this folder.

This assignment will focus on building simple classification models for predicting fetal health based on a number of clinical measurements known as cardiotocographic data.

The following introductory information was taken from the main Kaggle Dataset page for this data:

Context

Reduction of child mortality is reflected in several of the United Nationsâ Sustainable Development Goals and is a key indicator of human progress. The UN expects that by 2030, countries end preventable deaths of newborns and children under 5 years of age, with all countries aiming to reduce underâ5 mortality to at least as low as 25 per 1,000 live births.

Parallel to notion of child mortality is of course maternal mortality, which accounts for 295 000 deaths during and following pregnancy and childbirth (as of 2017). The vast majority of these deaths (94%) occurred in low-resource settings, and most could have been prevented.

In light of what was mentioned above, Cardiotocograms (CTGs) are a simple and cost accessible option to assess fetal health, allowing healthcare professionals to take action in order to prevent child and maternal mortality. The equipment itself works by sending ultrasound pulses and reading its response, thus shedding light on fetal heart rate (FHR), fetal movements, uterine contractions and more.

Data

This dataset contains 2126 records of features extracted from Cardiotocogram exams, which were then classified by three expert obstetritians into 3 classes:

  • Normal
  • Suspect
  • Pathological

The definitions of the columns are:

* baseline value - FHR baseline (beats per minute)
* accelerations - Number of accelerations per second
* fetal_movement - Number of fetal movements per second
* uterine_contractions - Number of uterine contractions per second
* light_decelerations - Number of light decelerations per second
* severe_decelerations - Number of severe decelerations per second
* prolongued_decelerations - Number of prolonged decelerations per second
* abnormal_short_term_variability - Percentage of time with abnormal short term variability
* mean_value_of_short_term_variability - Mean value of short term variability
* percentage_of_time_with_abnormal_long_term_variability - Percentage of time with abnormal long term variability
* mean_value_of_long_term_variability - Mean value of long term variability
* histogram_width - Width of FHR histogram
* histogram_min - Minimum (low frequency) of FHR histogram
* histogram_max - Maximum (high frequency) of FHR histogram
* histogram_number_of_peaks - Number of histogram peaks
* histogram_number_of_zeroes - Number of histogram zeros
* histogram_mode - Histogram mode
* histogram_mean - Histogram mean
* histogram_median - Histogram median
* histogram_variance - Histogram variance
* histogram_tendency - Histogram tendency

You can learn much more about the study behind this dataset from the following published paper:

  • https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6822315/

While in the original study and dataset, there were three classes for the target variable (Normal, Suspect, Pathological), we will convert this to a binary classification problem where 1 will be Suspect or Pathological and 0 will be Normal. Multi-class problems are a bit beyond the scope of this introduction to classification problems.

Step 3 - Data partitioning

Ok, itâs time to do an initial split of our data into training and test datasets.

For data partitioning, we will use the rsample package. Letâs allocate 80% of the records to our training set and 20% to the test set. Make sure you specify the strata = argument. After partitioning, confirm that the b_fetal_health proportions of 1âs and 0âs are as expected. Discuss.

set.seed(983) # Do NOT change this value
pct_train <- 0.8

# Create a "split object" based on an 80/20, stratified split. 
fetal_health_split <- rsample::initial_split(fetal_health,

# Create train and test dataframes based on the split

Correlation plot

Weâll start with a correlation plot. The tl.cex argument helps us display the plot by controlling the size of the text label. Itâs behavior is a little unpredictable but you can play around with various values.

The correlation plot shows that the histogram_mode, histogram_mean and histogram_median have a strong positive correlation which each other. These 3 variables also have a positive correlation with baseline.value variable. The histogram_min variable has negetive correlation with the light_decelerations, mean_value_of_short_term_variablity, histogram_width and histogram_number_of_peaks.

Now make a bunch of boxplots (or violin) that are grouped by the target variable. There are a few ways we can do this.

Instead of creating separate plots for each variable, we could create a faceted plot, where we facet by the variable. To do this, we need to reshape our data from wide to long. We can do this using tidyr::pivot_longer().

fetal_health_long <- fetal_health_train |> 
   pivot_longer(cols = -b_fetal_health,
                names_to = 'metric', values_to = 'value')

Now we can create the faceted plot using the long data.

fetal_health_long %>%
  ggplot() +

The faceted boxplot shows two fetal health groups for different variables where 0=normal and 1=suspect/pathological. Several variables such as abnormal_short_term_variability, percentage_of_time_with_abnormal_long_term_variability, and mean_value_of_long_term_variability have higher values in the non-normal group (1), which would indicate strong associations with abnormal fetal health. The histogram features mean, median, variance also show a higher average and more variability for suspect/pathological fetuses. Some predictors such as fetal_movement, prolonged_decelerations, and severe_decelerations, donât vary much across the groups which suggests that they may be less informative for classification. For most variables, there are outliers, meaning that some fetuses have very extreme clinical measurements.

Step 5 - Building and evaluation of predictive classification models

Now that you know a little more about the data, itâs time to start building a few classification models for b_fetal_health. We will use:

  • logistic regression
  • a simple decision tree
  • a random forest

We will start out using overall prediction accuracy as our metric but we might want to consider other metrics.

QUESTION Why might overall prediction accuracy not be the most appropriate metric to consider? What other metrics might be important and why?

The overall prediction accuracy can be misleading because it does not account for the class imbalance in a dataset. With 78% normal cases, a model predicting all cases as ânormalâ would achieve 78% accuracy while being clinically useless. More appropriate metrics include sensitivity/recall (to maximize detection of abnormal cases), specificity (to minimize false alarms) and precision. Given that the clinical stakes are so high, we want to make sure we catch as many at-risk cases as possible, so we need to prioritize sensitivity even if that means more false positives.

The null model

A very simple model would be to simply predict that b_fetal_health is equal to 0. On the training data we saw that weâd be ~78% accurate.

QUESTION What is the sensitivity and specificity of the null model?

For this null model that predicts all cases as normal (0), Sensitivity = 0% because the model never predicts abnormal (1), it catches zero true positive cases. It misses 100% of the at-risk fetuses. Specificity = 100% since the model always predicts normal (0), hence it will predict every truly normal case correctly (no false positives).

So, as we begin fitting more complicated models, remember that we need to outperform the null model to make it worth it to use more complicated models.

Model 1 - logistic regression model

For logistic regression, you must use tidymodels and you should see our class notes on logistic regression, in particular, the section titled âLogistic regression with tidymodelsâ. For this modeling technique, you must:

  • fit at least two different logistic regression models, each of which should have at least five variables. For your first model, use variables that you think might have predictive value based on the EDA you did. For the second model, use all of the variables.
  • use 5-fold cross-validation as our resampling scheme for model fitting,
  • just take the default threshold value of 0.5,
  • assess the modelâs performance on the training data (accuracy, sensitivity, specificity, confusion matrix),
  • use the model to make predictions on the test data and assess the modelâs performance on the test data,
  • discuss the results.

HACKER EXTRA CREDIT Create ROC curves and compute AUC for your logistic regression models. Discuss your interpretation of these plots.

Start by creating a classification model object using the appropriate engine = argument for logistic regression.

glm_spec <- logistic_reg(mode = "classification", engine = "glm")

Create a recipe for your first model which specifies the formula for your logistic regression model.

recipe_1 <-
  recipe(b_fetal_health ~ abnormal_short_term_variability + 
           mean_value_of_short_term_variability + 
           percentage_of_time_with_abnormal_long_term_variability + 
           mean_value_of_long_term_variability + histogram_mean,
           data = fetal_health_train)

Now create a workflow object and the recipe and model to it.

wf_1 <- workflow() %>% 
   add_recipe(recipe_1) %>% 
   add_model(glm_spec)

Now weâll create a folds object to use for k-crossfold validation.

set.seed(259)
fetal_health_folds <- vfold_cv(fetal_health_train, v = 5)
ctrl_preds <- control_resamples(save_pred = TRUE, save_workflow = TRUE)

Now you should fit your logistic regression model using folds object we just created.

fit_results_logreg1 <-
  wf_1 %>%
  fit_resamples(resamples = fetal_health_folds, control = ctrl_preds)

Now we can collect the metrics.

collect_metrics(fit_results_logreg1)

Letâs refit on entire training data set and make predictions on the test data. Recall from the notes that we use the last_fit function to do this. Then we can use the yardstick package to compute accuracy, sensitivity and specificity.

last_fit_logreg1 <- last_fit(wf_1, fetal_health_split)

# These are prediction on the test data

final_predicted_classes_1 <- collect_predictions(last_fit_logreg1)

# Accuracy
acc_test_logreg1 <- yardstick::accuracy(final_predicted_classes_1,
                                        estimate = .pred_class,
                                        truth = b_fetal_health, event_level = "second")

# Do similar things for sensitivity and specificity.
sens_test_logreg1 <- yardstick::sens(final_predicted_classes_1, 
                                     truth = b_fetal_health,
                                    estimate = .pred_class, event_level = "second")
  
spec_test_logreg1 <- yardstick::spec(final_predicted_classes_1,
                                     estimate = .pred_class,
                                     truth = b_fetal_health, event_level = "second")

# Combine the results into a single dataframe
  
stats_test_logreg1 <- bind_rows(acc_test_logreg1,
                                 sens_test_logreg1,
                                 spec_test_logreg1) |>
  mutate(data = 'test',
         model = 'logreg1')

# Confusion matrix
yardstick::conf_mat(final_predicted_classes_1,
                estimate = .pred_class,
                truth = b_fetal_health)

Model 1 logistic regression correctly classifies 86.4% of the test set compared to the null modelâs 78%, which is a significant improvement. However, sensitivity is unacceptably low at 54.7%, meaning there are 43 abnormal cases missed (false negatives). The specificity is great, at 95.5%, meaning there are few false alarms, but it shows that this model is conservative and biased toward ânormalâ predictions. There is still room for further improvement concerning sensitivity, given some abnormal cases were missed. Overall, the model demonstrates strong predictive value and is much more clinically useful than the null approach.

QUESTION Explain each of the values in the node in the third row from the top in the middle (light blue with values 0, 0.31 and 26%) What conditions need to be true for a case to end up in that node?

The node in the third row from the top, middle (light blue with values 0, 0.31, and 26%) represents cases that should have accelerations < 500e-6 and uterine_contractions >= 0.0025. Interpretation of the node values: 0: This is the predicted class representing normal fetal health. 0.31: The probability of being class 1 is 0.31. 26%: This node contains 26% of all the training data.

Now use augment() function along with yardstick::sens(), yardstick::spec(), and yardstick::conf_mat() to compute sensitivity, specificity, and the confusion matrix on the training data. In other words, we are just assessing how well the tree fits the data.

Notice in the code skeleton that Iâm explicitly specifying the yardstick package and a function from it. Iâm doing that because the spec function name clashes with another library we have loaded - you can see this by doing a help(spec). Also notice that we need event_level = "second" since â0â comes before â1â in the factor levels for b_fetal_health and itâs the â1ââs that are the thing we are trying to detect (abnormal results). We need `event_level = âsecondâ for accuracy, sensitivity and specificity calculations (we donât need it for the confusion matrix).

Final model comparisons

So, if you had to recommend a model to consider using in practice, which of the models (if any) would you recommend and why?

I would recommend the Logistic Regression Model 2 (all variables) for use. It offers the best 92.3% accuracy with 85.3% sensitivity and 94.3% specificity, supplemented by a AUC of 0.973. While the Random Forest shows a higher sensitivity of 97.6%, there is some overfitting, and its low specificity stands at 83.2%, making it unacceptable. Importantly, Logistic Regression Model 2 suffers no overfitting and presents interpretable coefficients. This model performed substantially better compared with the null model (78% accuracy, 0% sensitivity) and the simple decision tree (88% accuracy and 70.5% sensitivity).
